Moderate Foundationalism
 [Kazuhisa Todayama]
  Philosophy of Knowledge." p. 40 #Knowledge #Philosophy

 >[Foundational beliefs] need not be [inerrant].
 >Beliefs that are justified to such an extent that they can justify other beliefs in ways other than inferential [justification] by other [beliefs] break off the retrospective process of justification and ground other beliefs.
 >The idea that there are foundational beliefs that satisfy these conditions is called moderate [foundationalism].
